    * Matrix DFS:
      - To traverse all of the positions within a matrix, we can use Depth First Search (DFS), similar to how we would traverse a tree.
      In a matrix, we can move in all 4 directions, up, down, left, and right. Sometimes we can also move diagonally, but for the sake
      of simplicity, we will only consider the four directions in this lesson.
      Q: Count the unique paths from the top left to the bottom right. A single path may only move
       along 0's and can't visit the same cell more than once.
       - TC: 4^(n*m), where n is the number of rows and m is the number of columns
       - SC: O(n*m), Recursive call stack and Visited Array, where n is the number of rows and m is the
         number of columns.

       * Similar to backtracking. DFS is recursive in nature and we will be using recursion for this.
       * Firstly, we need to think of our base case(s). Well, we know that we can move in all 4 directions (horizontally and vertically)
       * We will have to try every path using backtracking since at any point in our path, we might not have a valid way to reach the
         bottom right, in which case, we will have to backtrack.
       * Since we are trying to find the number of unique paths, we need to keep count of the valid paths from each vertex.
       * The base cases:
            1. A unique path does not exist:
                - Since we are allowed to move in all 4 directions, it is possible that during our traversal, we end up going out of
                bounds. This means either our column, c , or our row, r becomes negative, or goes beyond the length of our matrix.
                It does not matter which of r and c goes out of bounds because we need a valid c AND a valid r to perform our search.
                We cannot perform a search on matrix[-1][3].
                - If we have already visited a coordinate this is also a base case. We do not want to count the same path multiple times.
                - If the current coordinate is 1, then a valid path does not exist through that coordinate, since we are not allowed to
                move through 1's.
            Since a valid path does not exist in all of the aforementioned cases, we will return 0, which denoates absence of a unqiue
            path.
            2. A unique path does exist:
                - If we have reached the right-most column and the bottom-most row, it must be the case that we have found a valid path.
                In this example, our definition of a valid path is if a path exists from matrix[0][0] to matrix[3][3].
            In this case we return 1 and this will be added to the total number of valid paths.
       * Implementation:
            - To ensure that we don't visit a coordinate more than once, we use a hash set to keep track of the visited coordinates.
                * A hash set is preferable over a list because we can insert and lookup coordinates in O(1) time. Alternatively we could
                have used a 2D boolean array of the same size as our grid to keep track of visited coordinates.
            - At any given coordinate r, c, we can recursively perform our DFS on (r+1, c), (r-1, c), (r, c+1), and (r, c-1). If our
            recursive call returns 1, it will be added to our count and if it returns 0, adding it to the count will not affect the count.
            - As we backtrack we make sure to remove the current coordinate from our visit hashset. This way, we can ensure to visit them
            again, but take a different direction and explore it a valid path exists from that direction.

       In Summary:
       To visualize the above on our matrix, we can break down our algorithm into finding the initial unique path, and then backtracking to
       find another potential unique path.
            1) Find the first unique path
            2) Backtrace to find another potential unique path


    * Matrix BFS:
      - Breadth-first search (BFS) can also be run on a matrix and is most commonly used to find the shortest path in a graph.
      - BFS on a graph is very similar to BFS on a tree, but with a few more edge cases and a different setup. Once again, we will
      only allow ourselves to move in 4 directions (horizontally and vertically).
      Q: Find the length of the shortest path from the top left of the grid to the bottom right.
        - We can also use DFS to accomplish this but BFS is more efficient.
        - TC: O(n*m), where n is the number of rows and m is the number of columns
        - SC: O(n*m) because of Queue and Visited Array
      - Similar to the previous less, we take the dimensions of our grid, which tells us where our bounds are. We will use a hash
      set to keep track of visited vertices. We will use a double ended queue to keep track of all visited vertices at each level
      and keep track of the current level.
      - We can initialize our queue to the first vertex, (0, 0) and mark it as visited. This is our starting point.
      - We are asked to find the length of the shortest path.
        * After our initial set up, we can initialize a length variable to 0. Then, just like BFS on trees, we can loop through our
        queue, level by level.
        * Here, when we pop from our queue, we get a r (row) and c (column). With trees, the next step was to visit the children of
        the popped node. Here, we visit the neighbors of the popped vertex. Here, we visit the neighbors of the popped vertex. We will
        continue this until we reach the target position which is at the bottom right of the grid.
        * To compute the positions of the 4 adjacent cells we can use an array neighbors = [[0,1],[0,-1],[1,0],[-1,0]].
        * Though this array does not technically store the positions of the neighbors, the array does represent the directions we can
        move in - right, left, up, down, respectively. All we need to do is add the direction to the current positon to get the new
        position.
        * The code in the inner most if statement is the same as what we had in DFS. If we are out of bounds, the coordinate is blocked
        or the vertex is already visited, we continue to the next iteration.
        * Otherwise, we append all the neighbors to the queue and add them to the hashset to ensure we don't visit them again. Notice
        how we add to the hashset as soon as we append to the queue. This way, we will never have the same element occur twice in our
        queue, which helps in making it more efficient in time complexity, which we will discuss later.
      - TC:
            * Since we are never visiting a coordinate twice, in the worst case, we end up visiting each coordinate at most once. If n
            is the number of rows and m is the number of columns, this gives us a time complexity of O(n*m).
      - SC:
            * The space complexity is O(n*m) as well. This is because we are storing all the vertices in the queue and the hash set.
            The queue can have at most n * m vertices and the hash set can also have at most n * m vertices.


