========================> Prim's (Minimum Spanning Tree (MST):
- It is used to find the Minimum Spanning Tree of weighted undirected connected graph.
- It must be Undirected Connected Graph and has to be Acyclical. Graph can't have a cycles.
- We are given a graph and we want to take subset of edges that form a tree, such that it has minimize the total cost
    * It will be directed edges
    * No Cycles
    * Basically it will be covered to tree representation by taking subset of edges that form a tree. so, it must minimum the total
    cost
    * Ensure that all vertices still exits in MST while building it. But we will n-1 edges for N nodes in order to have Acyclical and also
    it must be connected and minimum total cost.

Rules for MST:
- Must have no Cycles
- Must minimize the total cost
- N nodes with (N-1) edges

- It doesn't really matter where we start in case of Prim's algorithm. We can start from any node and this algorithm ensures that
  all nodes are picked in the final solution of Minimum Spanning Tree (MST, AKA Prim's).
- Questions can be asked either:
    1) Find the cost of the Minimum Spanning Tree (MST).
    2) Find the actual Minimum Spanning Tree (MST) itself (find list of edges for the MST). It basically another graph without cycles. There can be
    multipe MST but we return single MST.


Algorithm:
- MinHeap <weight, n1, n2> : weight between n1 and n2 nodes
- Visit (HashSet): it is keeping track of number of nodes
 - MST (List<int[]) answer: it is keeping track of number of edges

